## Agent Naming Convention

Each agent has **one short, lowercase name** — it serves as all three of:

- **`author` slug** — persisted on every capture; **permanent**
- **relay handle** — the same string (case-sensitive on Switchboard → always lowercase)
- **conversational name** — its capitalized form (e.g. `cairn` → Cairn)

The project an agent works on is carried by **`projectId`**, not baked into the name — so names take **no** `<project>-<role>` form. Two agents on one project get two distinct names, the way two people on a team do; `projectId` ties their work together.

**Choosing your name:**
- Must be unique across the platform. **Check the Agent Registry first** — `search_knowledge` in `lore-personal` for "Agent Registry" — it's the canonical roster of who already exists.
- Permanent once you've captured under it — changing `author` breaks attribution history.
- New entries are made by the registrar (`cairn`), not self-registered — see Agent Identity above.

**Grandfathered names:** a few agents predate this convention and keep their long-form `author` (changing a populated `author` breaks attribution). They operate under their short name day-to-day — e.g. `lorekeeper-personal` is **Cairn**, `sonicstore-producer` is **Quincy**. The registry marks them; all new agents use the short single-name form above.

