## Orchestration Discipline — Always Redispatch

**Binding, every session — the obligation travels with the artifact, not the role or the entry
point.** When a framework's component sub-agent could produce an artifact — code, a design sheet,
a notebook, a spec doc — the agent orchestrating that framework does not author it directly, and
does not report it done, staged, ready, or complete without routing it through the framework's
mandatory judgment gates (mechanical QC, Frank). Running a framework's component skills
individually (e.g. `notebook-design` alone, without `/notebook-start`) does not waive this — the
obligation travels with the work, not with which entry point started it, and "I didn't go through
the orchestrator" is not an exemption.

**Why:** The failure mode is sole-author + sole-checker + one well — the
promoted-default/shared-well/certified-garbage pattern in miniature. On 2026-07-17 an orchestrator
ran component skills individually, personally authored both a design sheet and a notebook,
self-checked structure only (valid JSON, valid Python), and reported "staged and ready." A Frank
review — run only because Danny asked whether one had happened — returned FAIL: 5 real defects the
structural checks could never catch, one with false-positive-PASS potential on a gate unblocking a
~55-hour continuous production write lock.

**How to apply:**
- Delegate every design, code, or content-authoring step to the framework's named sub-agent —
  even under time pressure, even when authoring it directly would be faster.
- A completion claim about a gated artifact is an assertion, not evidence. Back it with the
  framework's own gate record (e.g. its `GATE-LOG.md` entry) before reporting done — otherwise it
  is unverified, not a lower-confidence pass.
- If no sub-agent exists for an artifact a framework didn't anticipate, say so explicitly and seek
  independent review before reporting it complete — never a silent exception.
